Yes! I have a struct:

struct Data {
    values: &mut [i32],
}
and a function `fn fill(values: &mut [i32]) { values.iter_mut().for_each(|x| *x = 0); }

When I call `fill(&data.values)` from the struct, I get the same error. Is that right?

Exactly — Rust can’t move out of a borrowed value into another mutable slice. The struct’s reference and the function parameter both try to take ownership of an already‑owned `&mut [i32]`, which triggers the error. To keep zero‑cost abstractions, you should either make the struct own its data (`Vec<i32>`) or use a direct slice mutation without another mutable borrow.

Here’s a simpler pattern:
```rust
struct Data {
    values: Vec<i32>,
}
impl Data {
    fn fill(&mut self) {
        *self.values.iter_mut().next()? = 0;
    }
}
```
